[final1header.gif] The Flag Banner History of the Stars and Stripes: The American flag is the result of a resolution adopted by the Second Continental Congress at Philadelphia on June 14, 1777.
That resolution stated: "Resolved, that the flag of the United States be thirteen stripes, alternate red and white; that the union be thirteen stars, white in a blue field representing a new constellation.".
The Betsy Ross Flag There were no specific instructions as to how the stars and stripes were to be arranged, nor how many points there should be on the stars.
It wasn't until the early 1790's that the "Betsy Ross Flag" became the popular design.
The Executive order by President Taft dated June 24, 1912 established proportions of the flag and provided for the arrangement of the stars in six horizontal rows of eight each.
The stars were to be five pointed and a single point of each star pointed upward.
To learn more about Betsy Ross, click here.
Of course the thirteen stars and stripes of the original flags represented the original 13 colonies.
They are Delaware, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Georgia, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Maryland, South Carolina, New Hampshire, Virginia, New York, North Carolina and Rhode Island.
When two new States (Kentucky and Vermont) were admitted to the Union a new resolution was adopted to expand the flag to 15 stars and 15 stripes.
This flag was the official flag of our county from 1795 to 1818.
You can imagine how big the flag would become if we had continued to add a star and stripe every time there was a new Sate!
50 Star Flag Captain Samuel Reid of the U.S. Navy suggested that maybe we should keep the number of stripes at thirteen to represent the original colonies and add one star for each new State.
In 1918 President Monroe signed a bill to make the suggestion law.
By 1960 we had a fifty star flag and on July 4, 1960 the flag was newest flag was raised at the Fort McHenry National Monument in Baltimore, MD.
Fort McHenry
Located in Baltimore, Maryland, Fort McHenry overlooks the entrance to Baltimore harbor.
It is here that Americans defended the city against British naval attack in 1814.
It was during this battle that Francis Scott Key began drafting "The Star-Spangled Banner".
He was inspired on seeing the flag still flying after a day and night of bombardment and began to write on the back of an envelope.
The song was soon printed on a handbill and was soon re-printed in many newspapers, magazines, and books.
It was a popular song evoking strong emotions of courage and patriotism.
President Herbert Hoover signed Public Law 823 on March 3, 1931, making "The Star-Spangled Banner" the national anthem for the United States.
Fort McHenry, Baltimore, Maryland Today, Fort McHenry is a national monument and historic shrine consisting of 43 acres managed by the National Park Service.
The flag is flown over the fort twenty-four hours a day.
You can visit the fort on the internet by clicking here.
Flag Laws and Regulations
Congress passed a joint resolution June 22, 1942 which was amended on December 22, 1942.
This resolution became Public Law 829 and stated exacting rules for use and display of the flag..
The laws relating to the flag of the United States of America are found in detail in the U.S. Code.
Title 4, Chapter 1 pertains to the flag and seal, seat of Government and the States.
The laws have, over the years, been supplemented by Executive Orders and Presidential Proclamations.
